Dialogue: 0,0:02:14.92,0:02:18.87,Default,,0,0,0,,3:00 am on December 8th, 1941.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:19.55,0:02:22.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Simultaneously with the outbreak of the war on the Pacific, {/At the same time as the news had arrived of }
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.43,0:02:26.20,Default,,0,0,0,,a coded telegram had arrived, \Nannouncing the successful landing on the Malay Peninsula.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:26.20,0:02:31.06,Default,,0,0,0,,The one who received it was Lieutenant-General Sakai, \Ncommander of the 23rd Japanese Army.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:31.06,0:02:34.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Without delay, he amassed his men \Nat the border of the Kowloon Peninsula.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:34.47,0:02:39.63,Default,,0,0,0,,To his forces, numbering about 30 000 troops, \Nhe gave the order to commence the attack on Hong Kong.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:39.63,0:02:45.65,Sign,,0,0,190,,{\blur0.8\c&HE4E9E1&\bord0\xshad6\yshad3\4c&H656363&\b1\4a&H28&}Episode 6 \N {\fs130} The Fall of Hong Kong
Dialogue: 0,0:02:55.17,0:03:00.24,Default,,0,0,0,,In preparation for the seizure of Hong Kong, \Nthe Japanese army had conducted a sufficient research,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.24,0:03:03.49,Default,,0,0,0,,came up with advanced detailed plans \Nand made timely arrangements.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:03.49,0:03:06.62,Default,,0,0,0,,The enemy had prepared a line of fortifications \Non Kowloon Peninsula{ in order to stop us}:
Dialogue: 0,0:03:06.62,0:03:08.98,Default,,0,0,0,,from Shau Kei Wan to Golden Hill{金山 - literally "golden mine", maybe replace with kinzan}, \Nto {Upper }Shing Mun Reservoir. {HA also adds here "to Lion Rock." for w/e reason, I don't hear it but maybee it's in the next line}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:08.98,0:03:15.04,Default,,0,0,0,,On this mountain ridge, to the south of the recess, \Nis the heavily fortified position, dubbed "Gin Drinkers Line." {honestly, no clue what's this shinzan, may be "recess in the mountains" but HA's is being constant about translating it as "lion rock" but it'd make no sense, as irl lion rock is to the south of gin drinkers and lit of this is "connecting to the south of this shinzan"}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.48,0:03:20.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Gin Drinkers Line, so peculiarly named after the soldiers \Ngetting intoxicated from drinking too much Gin, {actually he just explains in japanese who "gin drinker" is so I'm having to make shit up here}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:20.20,0:03:23.01,Default,,0,0,0,,is a well thought through \Nline of defensive fortifications.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.01,0:03:27.01,Default,,0,0,0,,The enemy commander, Major General Maltby, \Nin anticipation of the outbreak of the war,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:27.01,0:03:31.25,Default,,0,0,0,,bolstered the Gin Drinkers Line yesterday \Nwith the fresh British 2nd Royal Scots Battalion. {Most of 1941 passed without active duty for the regiment, and with growing concerns about the stability of the Far East, the 2nd Battalion, still based at Hong Kong, moved into defensive positions around the colony. On 8 December, the Battle of Hong Kong began a few hours after the attack on Pearl Harbor; after bitter fighting, the garrison surrendered on Christmas Day. The newly formed 12th Battalion was disbanded and reformed as the 2nd Battalion in May 1942.[53]}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:31.25,0:03:34.00,Default,,0,0,0,,In addition to 2nd and 14th Punjab Battalions from India, {The 5/7th Battalion, Rajput Regiment[30] took up garrison at Hong Kong in June 1937 followed by the 2/14th Battalion, Punjab Regiment in November 1940.}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:34.00,0:03:36.94,Default,,0,0,0,,the 5th and 7th Rajput battalions were redeployed as well{, it seems}. {arrangement (of resources); deployment; stationing; posting; disposition; configuration; layout}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:37.55,0:03:40.81,Default,,0,0,0,,It appears, the odds are decisively stacked on our side. {superiority; superior power; predominance; preponderance​}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:40.82,0:03:43.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Let us fight the enemy fair and square \Nwith time-proven tactics. {I hope he means this by "successful way"}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:43.68,0:03:49.52,Default,,0,0,0,,How many days will it take for the 1st artillery regiment to arrive to position, from which they can shell the enemy? {gaining total control (of people or counties); suppression; oppression; control; mastery; ascendancy; supremacy} {it's "reach" in HA's ver for w/e reason}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.52,0:03:51.77,Default,,0,0,0,,They'll probably take care of it in a week.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:51.77,0:03:53.75,Default,,0,0,0,,You think they'll manage in a week?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:54.69,0:03:55.67,Default,,0,0,0,,They'll have to.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:55.67,0:03:56.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Good.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:57.11,0:04:01.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Set the deadline for breaking through \Nthe Gin Drinkers Line on one week! {it was "The preparation period for breaking through the Gin Drinkers Line is one week." in HA's ver but that doesn't make sense: they won't decide on a date to start Pacific war based on the hong kong capture date, so it has to be something like "after a week's bombardment, we'll begin the general offensive" which is a bit closer to what happened irl, but still makes little sense}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:03.84,0:04:07.29,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll concentrate the bombardment \Non a mountain pass next to the Golden Hill. {this shinzan again, HA has it "Lion rock" again. He might just be right, but he is still not pointing at where the Lion rock is located irl and it's not even marked on their map so might as well be "mountain recess" as I assumed, but that'd make sense here as lit is "midway between shinzan and Golden hill"; amazingly, if I go the dumb way and write shinzan on-yomi as 新山 that would be the chinese name for Johor Bahru, with which I thought I was done in ep5; I deadass checked every on-yomi reading for every mountain in hong kong and I've still no clue what's shinzan - https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_mountains,_peaks_and_hills_in_Hong_Kong}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.29,0:04:10.48,Default,,0,0,0,,I would ask the artillery detachments \Nto target the middle of this area.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:10.48,0:04:13.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Lets throw in the full might of our 24cm howitzers. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Type_96_24_cm_howitzer}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:13.96,0:04:18.09,Default,,0,0,0,,If we break through in just one place, the rest of the line \Nwould be exposed from the flanks and rear.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:18.84,0:04:22.51,Default,,0,0,0,,In the meantime, deploy the division's main force \Nto the east and west of Tai Mo Shan. {believing HA, might replace with "the province's highest peak in the golden mountain area" or smt like that since nobody knows this one}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:22.51,0:04:25.28,Default,,0,0,0,,At the first opportunity, \Nthey'll topple the Gin Drinkers Line. {no clue what's the first word, ki (tree/mood) wo mite? kyu (moment) wo mite?; lit: at kyumitei, all at once, they'll break through ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:25.28,0:04:28.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, the same tactics we used \Nin the Russo-Japanese War to seize Port Arthur. {no clue what's that senkun, believing HA}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:39.27,0:04:42.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Hong Kong is made up of two administrative subdivisions:
Dialogue: 0,0:04:42.04,0:04:45.40,Default,,0,0,0,,the Kowloon Peninsula, directly bordering \Nthe Chinese mainland, and Hong Kong Island.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.40,0:04:47.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Facing them are the forces under Major General Maltby:
Dialogue: 0,0:04:47.94,0:04:55.62,Default,,0,0,0,,from Britain, India, Canada - each one presented \Nby two battalions{I hope he means this by "centered on two battalions"}, numbering a total of about 12 000 men.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:23.01,0:05:27.41,Default,,0,0,0,,The meticulous preparation paid off, \Nas when the Japanese finally attacked, following the plan,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:27.41,0:05:30.68,Default,,0,0,0,,they met no resistance whatsoever \Nfrom the British defenders. {I hope he means this by "were immediately hit everywhere"}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:31.28,0:05:33.66,Default,,0,0,0,,However, the British Army as well
Dialogue: 0,0:05:33.66,0:05:37.17,Default,,0,0,0,,had yet an ace up their sleeve, \Nwhich is the defensive Gin Drinkers Line. {/was expexting to defend on ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:38.38,0:05:45.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Only having thoroughly flattened the British positions with unrelenting shelling, ordering the infantry to advance -
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.06,0:05:47.84,Default,,0,0,0,,such was the discreet operational plan \Nthe Japanese came up with.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:47.84,0:05:50.61,Default,,0,0,0,,With that prospect in mind, \Nthe front line battalion commander
Dialogue: 0,0:05:50.61,0:05:54.06,Default,,0,0,0,,sent one of his subordinates, the First Lieutenant \Nout on a reconnaissance mission, {this shokosekko again, still no clue what's shoko, but sekko is again certainly "reconnoitering party; scout (army)"; also no clue what's ichi, it's literally "one/1" but I don't think that's how "first Lieutenant works in japanese" and as a name ichi can be only feminine} {HA has it here "Lieutenant Toichi Wakabayashi" somehow but I clearly can't hear him mentioned directly yet, and this is what I could\Nfind about him: During the war, Wakabayashi went into Hong Kong with his regiment, which arrived at the front later than other units. On 9 December, his regimental commander reconnoitered the Needle Hill area and found Shing Mun Redoubt lightly guarded. He was entrusted to conduct additional reconnaissance later that day and had the same conclusion. His commander decided to send a battalion to launch a night attack against the position, and Wakabayashi’s company participated in the attack. He and his men rushed to the top of the Redoubt and he left a marking at the entrance of “Shaftesbury Avenue,” one of the tunnels of the Redoubt. As the action was not approved by the higher command, he was somehow blamed by his regimental commander for taking the position without order, and was forbidden to play an active role throughout the battle. His battalion was sent as the final reserve of the division and was not sent to the Island until 24 December. This possibly explained his survival. - so apparently it's really him who's being sent, but the name is not said explicitly, apparently...?}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.06,0:05:56.20,Default,,0,0,0,,to have him personally lead the forward unit. {no clue what's ikko, also not sure what's hiki here so believing HA}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:56.20,0:05:59.87,Default,,0,0,0,,They were tasked with probing \Ninto the British positions in the highlands. {to investigate; to probe into; to spy on; to sound out}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:13.37,0:06:14.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Lieutenant, there it is...
Dialogue: 0,0:06:14.96,0:06:17.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. Artillery observation post.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:18.88,0:06:19.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Alright,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:20.38,0:06:21.33,Default,,0,0,0,,let's get a closer look.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.33,0:06:22.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Watch out!
Dialogue: 0,0:06:22.90,0:06:26.34,Default,,0,0,0,,In a moonlight that bright, \Nthe enemy will see{/discover} you immediately.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:33.08,0:06:35.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Look, the heavens are on our side.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:45.19,0:06:49.24,Default,,0,0,0,,This lieutenant was an officer who had risen from the ranks. {lit: working one's way up commissioned officer}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:49.24,0:06:52.22,Default,,0,0,0,,His copious combat experience \Neventually made that possible.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:05.90,0:07:07.48,Default,,0,0,0,,No one's manning it.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.48,0:07:09.28,Default,,0,0,0,,What could be the meaning of this?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:09.28,0:07:13.74,Default,,0,0,0,,The prerequisite for breaking through the Gin Drinkers Line \Nis the neutralization of this observation post.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.74,0:07:15.51,Default,,0,0,0,,And that's something we can do.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:15.51,0:07:17.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Lieutenant, are you serious?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:17.24,0:07:18.45,Default,,0,0,0,,The surprise is on our side.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:18.45,0:07:20.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't go. It's reckless.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:20.55,0:07:22.46,Default,,0,0,0,,It's only 21 of us here. Besides...
Dialogue: 0,0:07:22.46,0:07:24.21,Default,,0,0,0,,"Besides" what? Spit it out.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:24.50,0:07:26.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. You were tasked with a reconnaissance mission.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.71,0:07:27.71,Default,,0,0,0,,This is insubordination. {HA: This is an act of disobedience.} {he seems indeed to be Toichi Wakabayashi, remember wiki info I found on him before?}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:27.71,0:07:30.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Drop it{/don't worry}. We're just doing a bit of mole extermination. {this is literal, not sure why he'd choose moles, maybe because they dig themselves into the ground}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:30.48,0:07:31.15,Default,,0,0,0,,However...
Dialogue: 0,0:07:31.15,0:07:34.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Only he, who remains at all times composed \Nis good at decision making. {I really hope he says "the most brilliant display of your heroism is having a sound judgement with a completely cool head" tho not sure about any part of it; HA had it "On the battlefield, there are many things that require arbitrary judgment" and in quotes for w/e reason so I figured it might be some sun tzu quote but no, I can't find a source of it or a general named sukobu ooshi, but HA's ver sounds also very believeable, maybe even more so than mine, no clue what's ooshi in the end}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:34.72,0:07:35.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:36.16,0:07:38.23,Default,,0,0,0,,You enter the battle prepared for anything. {adapting oneself to the requirements of the moment; playing by ear; ad hoc approach}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:38.23,0:07:40.19,Default,,0,0,0,,You take decisions without hesitating.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:40.19,0:07:44.10,Default,,0,0,0,,This decision has to be made by someone, \Nso I don't think it's necessarily punishable. {lit is "i don't think the action of judgment is (not) always; (not) necessarily; (not) entirely; (not) all goes against the military rules" - really sounds like he ends the sentence after "(not) always; (not) necessarily; (not) entirely; (not) all" so I'm generally unsure}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.10,0:07:45.67,Default,,0,0,0,,I knew you'd understand.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:46.46,0:07:47.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Will you join me now?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:47.69,0:07:48.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:48.76,0:07:50.11,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll make a short work of it.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:50.11,0:07:50.55,Default,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:50.94,0:07:52.11,Default,,0,0,0,,A shortest work, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:52.96,0:07:53.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Gather! {/get together}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:56.53,0:08:00.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Listen, I jump in first, \Nthen you jump after and follow my footsteps. {no clue what he means by "uniformly; evenly; equally; indiscriminately; across the board", but with next line in mind, HA's "in line" makes sense}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:00.08,0:08:02.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Any silhouette you see outside our line is an enemy! {lit: think that everything that moves to the left and right is enemy}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:47.06,0:08:48.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:07.79,0:09:09.07,Default,,0,0,0,,{add w/e here, I don't hear anything}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.93,0:09:11.53,Default,,0,0,0,,{same}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:36.32,0:09:38.34,Default,,0,0,0,,What's the Japanese troop count? {lit: japanese numbers are?}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:38.91,0:09:41.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Probably 200-300, up to 400-500.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.35,0:09:45.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Our garrison numbers 100 men at best. \NAsk battalion commander for reinforcements at once!
Dialogue: 0,0:09:45.66,0:09:46.41,Default,,0,0,0,,There's the phone.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:47.42,0:09:48.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay!
Dialogue: 0,0:09:48.32,0:09:49.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Hello.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:49.66,0:09:50.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Hello!
Dialogue: 0,0:09:50.40,0:09:52.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Keep calm. No need to panic. {guess, hantai is reverse; opposite; inverse; contrary but idk what it means, maybe "do the opposite"; HA has it "be calm"}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:59.03,0:10:00.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Battalion commander, sir!
Dialogue: 0,0:10:00.30,0:10:01.66,Default,,0,0,0,,We've an emergency! {state of emergency; emergency; crisis}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:01.66,0:10:02.72,Default,,0,0,0,,What is it? Calm down.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:02.72,0:10:03.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:03.90,0:10:06.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Our reconnaissance party clashed with the enemy.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:06.72,0:10:08.52,Default,,0,0,0,,A fierce firefight ensued.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:08.52,0:10:09.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Damn it.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:10.04,0:10:14.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Indeed. Things are not going according to plan. {lit; it became a problematic thing}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:17.70,0:10:20.47,Default,,0,0,0,,I believe, they're after the glory of beating others to it. {lit: the fame/glory of solo raid on an enemy's camp (for glory)​ was probably what they aimed at}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:21.58,0:10:22.75,Default,,0,0,0,,What's done is done. {cannot be helped; unavoidable}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:24.33,0:10:28.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Order the 3rd Battalion to attack immediately, \Nwith the 2nd Battalion covering them. {/supporting}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:31.04,0:10:32.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Commander, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:32.38,0:10:35.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Doing so would bring to a disarray \Nall the army's operational planning.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:35.84,0:10:38.09,Default,,0,0,0,,reconnaissance party are not lambs for slaughter. {lit: we can't letting (someone) die without helping}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.58,0:10:39.62,Default,,0,0,0,,No, but still...
Dialogue: 0,0:10:40.01,0:10:41.68,Default,,0,0,0,,The division commander was rash to... {no clue what's ichiwo, may be "tentatively; for the time being" but they never mentioned it before; no clue what's kakka either, and not sure which division commander they refer to - most likely the reconnaissance party one; HA's: the intentions of ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:41.68,0:10:43.26,Default,,0,0,0,,I take full responsibility.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:43.26,0:10:44.01,Default,,0,0,0,,It's an order.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:44.87,0:10:47.61,Default,,0,0,0,,They've not a notion of the {/what is }military discipline!
Dialogue: 0,0:10:49.02,0:10:52.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Make sure to reprimand their entire unit, \Nas soon as this reconnaissance party is back! {lit: immediately withdraw ... to the unit they belong to and ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:52.76,0:10:53.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Roger!
Dialogue: 0,0:10:53.42,0:10:57.54,Default,,0,0,0,,The army must, at all times, base all its actions \Non the prudent operational plan.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:57.54,0:10:59.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Arbitrary actions are unacceptable! {/self-willed/selfish/on your own}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:09.22,0:11:10.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Alright, let's get in there. {to plunge into; to charge into; to rush into; to ram into; to crash into}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:11.20,0:11:12.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Charge! {act. "continue/advance/keep on"}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:53.98,0:11:54.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Commander-in-chief!
Dialogue: 0,0:11:55.32,0:11:58.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Reinforcements! Please send in reinforcements!
Dialogue: 0,0:11:58.06,0:11:59.71,Default,,0,0,0,,We're swept away if you don't! {annihilation; total destruction; complete destruction; crushing defeat}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:00.13,0:12:01.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Just try and listen to this rumble!
Dialogue: 0,0:12:01.69,0:12:06.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Impossible. The Japanese engaged us here as well! \NNo prospect for a counterattack. Disengage and fall back!
Dialogue: 0,0:12:27.83,0:12:32.37,Default,,0,0,0,,You order us to fall back, and yet, all the routes \Nfor retreating{/exits behind us} are by now in Japanese hands! {to get a hold of; to obtain; to seize; to catch; to arrest}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:32.91,0:12:35.71,Default,,0,0,0,,That's exactly why such "mole fortifications" \Nare good for nothing! {/why I hate}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:10.79,0:13:12.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Forward!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:12.16,0:13:13.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Forward!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:15.92,0:13:16.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Division commander!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:17.92,0:13:18.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Look there.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:20.11,0:13:21.84,Default,,0,0,0,,They did the bastards.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:22.32,0:13:23.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Ridiculous!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:27.08,0:13:30.87,Default,,0,0,0,,We don't want the enemy to reoccupy fortifications \Nwe secured with so much trouble, {lit: thinking there's no need to return to the enemy the position seized with all that trouble}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:30.87,0:13:35.87,Default,,0,0,0,,so I asked the front line commander \Nto halt the further advance for the time being.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:35.87,0:13:38.70,Default,,0,0,0,,At least until the currently occupied position \Nis duly secured.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:38.70,0:13:43.04,Default,,0,0,0,,If we let them act this way all the time, we can shove \Nour operational plans to where the sun doesn't shine! {spoiled; spoilt; ruined; wasted (chance, etc.); messed up; destroyed; (coming to) nothing}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:43.04,0:13:46.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, we positively must reprimand them. \NBreach of discipline is a grave offense! {extreme; excessive; terrible; intense; severe; serious; tremendous; heavy (damage)} {unsure it's not hanaganashi - unappealing; uninteresting; lacking charm} {funny to hear about discipline from the Japs, who violated nearly every geneva convention rule}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:46.38,0:13:50.87,Default,,0,0,0,,However, they made it possible for our army \Nto capture in a span of one night
Dialogue: 0,0:13:50.87,0:13:52.58,Default,,0,0,0,,what seemed to take a week to subjugate.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:52.58,0:13:57.05,Default,,0,0,0,,What, then, do you suppose we're preparing \Nthe battle plans for? Formulating operations?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:57.05,0:14:00.69,Default,,0,0,0,,By closing our eyes to a single such foray for glory, \Nwe'll screw up all the planning! {lit: if we allow/forgive such a solo raid on an enemy's camp (for glory), operation/strategy will only be in disorder; chaos; confusion; mayhem}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:00.69,0:14:03.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't you see a silver lining to it? \NIt's good to be prepared for anything. {adapting oneself to the requirements of the moment; playing by ear; ad hoc approach - I tl'd it this way the last time}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:04.34,0:14:07.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Besides, it took a great deal of weight \Noff my own shoulders.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:08.76,0:14:10.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Isn't that right, sir?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:10.30,0:14:14.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, at any rate, reprimanding this reconnaissance party \Nshould be our first priority. {deciding first; settling (a matter) first; first priority}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:14.97,0:14:16.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Regarding that,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:17.36,0:14:19.48,Default,,0,0,0,,if we examine our current situation,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:19.48,0:14:24.14,Default,,0,0,0,,they have indeed opened a large gap \Nin the enemy positions on Gin Drinkers Line.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:24.14,0:14:28.26,Default,,0,0,0,,All over the front line, the British troops \Nare reported to be slowly falling back.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:28.26,0:14:32.88,Default,,0,0,0,,In the wake of this, all the front line commanders \Ninsist that we take advantage of it{/this opportunity}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:32.88,0:14:37.54,Default,,0,0,0,,by immediately renewing the advance, \Nand seizing as many land from the enemy as we can. {unsusre what he means: all at once, capturing advance}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:40.10,0:14:41.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:43.14,0:14:44.19,Default,,0,0,0,,What about you?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:44.76,0:14:45.94,Default,,0,0,0,,I commit to it. {/support}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:45.94,0:14:46.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Alright.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:46.64,0:14:49.35,Default,,0,0,0,,We should make arrangements \Nfor an emergency change of {operational }plans,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:49.35,0:14:51.97,Default,,0,0,0,,and launch an all-out attack along the entire front!
Dialogue: 0,0:15:45.04,0:15:48.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's redeploy our entire {British }army to the Hong Kong Island.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:48.38,0:15:50.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Our new ally Generalissimo Chiang Kai-shek{ and his allied armies}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:50.42,0:15:54.06,Default,,0,0,0,,promised to attack the Japanese \Nfrom behind on the Kowloon Peninsula.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:54.06,0:15:57.83,Default,,0,0,0,,This option is favorable to a futile defense of peninsula \Nwith more bloody battles. {lit: it's more effective than defending kowloon peninsula with hard fight; close game; struggle; tight contest}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:00.43,0:16:01.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Alright.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:01.22,0:16:05.38,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll order all the troops on the Kowloon Peninsula \Nto withdraw orderly to the Hong Kong island{added, he doesn't specify what does he mean by HK}.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:07.42,0:16:13.47,Default,,0,0,0,,The operation of conquering the Gin Drinkers Line, \Nwhich was initially believed to take a week or more,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:13.47,0:16:15.59,Default,,0,0,0,,was completed in just three days.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:16.48,0:16:18.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Kowloon Peninsula firmly under their control,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:18.82,0:16:22.79,Default,,0,0,0,,the Japanese troops \Nentered the continental part of Hong Kong unopposed. {lit: entered kowloon part of hk}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:49.35,0:16:52.84,Default,,0,0,0,,At 9:05 am on December 13th,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:52.84,0:16:56.57,Default,,0,0,0,,the Japanese military representatives{/staff} \Nwith some of the English women in tow,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:56.57,0:17:00.92,Default,,0,0,0,,landed on the Hong Kong Island, \Ntasked with encouraging a capitulation. {HA: to plead with the British women to encourage surrender. - no clue where plead part came from, michiannai toshite is "as a guidance; showing the way; guide" but i still dont know what it means - why'd they ask a woman to guide them also to an island in plain sight? I'd assume it means "to ensure safe passage"}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:16.51,0:17:17.27,Default,,0,0,0,,However,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:17.62,0:17:19.47,Default,,0,0,0,,the British reply was
Dialogue: 0,0:17:19.89,0:17:20.74,Default,,0,0,0,,"Never". {pretty sure it was "no" irl}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:21.72,0:17:26.00,Default,,0,0,0,,With a single word, the commander \Nruled out the surrender as a possibility. {lit: in other words, it was one word that meant they'll never surrender}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:33.88,0:17:38.16,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese attack was renewed \Nand the air raids continued.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:38.93,0:17:42.10,Default,,0,0,0,,The scope of damage inflicted \Ndwarfed anything seen before. {unsure what he means: that never before intensity to inflict (damage); to deal; to give/to increase; to gather (e.g. speed); to pick up thing}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:51.67,0:17:54.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Then, on December 17th,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.86,0:17:58.03,Default,,0,0,0,,the Japanese army had once again \Nput forward a surrender offer.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:58.85,0:17:59.70,Default,,0,0,0,,However...
Dialogue: 0,0:17:59.70,0:18:03.09,Default,,0,0,0,,The Governor-general of Hong Kong \Nas well as the Commander-in-Chief
Dialogue: 0,0:18:03.09,0:18:06.83,Default,,0,0,0,,refused flatly to enter any kind of negotiations \Nregarding our surrender.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:06.83,0:18:08.87,Default,,0,0,0,,It is absolutely out of question.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:08.87,0:18:13.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Additionally, I will take this chance to inform you \Nthat we are no longer inclined to answer
Dialogue: 0,0:18:13.50,0:18:17.85,Default,,0,0,0,,to any propositions from the Japanese army, \Npertaining this matter. {lit: we're not prepared to receive the contact from ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:26.64,0:18:28.50,Default,,0,0,0,,A squall is likely to come soon.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:29.50,0:18:31.44,Default,,0,0,0,,The moonrise is late tonight. {no clue what's the message of this}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:37.67,0:18:40.57,Default,,0,0,0,,At 9 o'clock tonight, commence the crossing. {actually "landing" but I think he means "embark to later land" because you can't exactly time landing like that}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:42.22,0:18:44.01,Default,,0,0,0,,As a matter of fact, in my division,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:44.01,0:18:48.87,Default,,0,0,0,,there is a Los Angeles Olympic Games nominee \Nin breaststroke swimming, Lieutenant Koike Reizo. {I can't find any records of irl this guy taking part in this operation, but his name is spelled out clearly} {also technically "winner/champion" but he only was silver medalist so idk} {I think this is the event they are talking about, although irl it took place on dec 13th and here they depict a rather later date: A group of swimmers from the 38th Division, led by two officers, gather on the 13th to receive special training to swim across the harbour. The plan was then dropped as the group suffered losses during a British bombardment as whilst they assembled at Kai Tak.}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:49.29,0:18:54.77,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll form a volunteer division with Lieutenant as its core \Nand have them swim across to distract the enemy. {lit: bring to disorder; chaos; confusion; mayhem the enemy base/position}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:54.77,0:18:56.17,Default,,0,0,0,,We've no need for that.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:08.81,0:19:13.81,Default,,0,0,0,,In that thick black smoke, the British can't see us \Nrowing right past them even 50 meters away. {lit: from the british position, kaijo is not supposed to be seen - not exactly sure what's kaijo but has to do with the sea/landing/swimming/sea surface/traffic}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:13.81,0:19:17.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Additionally, this rain renders the sea surface \Nimpenetrable to the eye. {lit: in this weather, kaijo is a complete darkness}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:18.65,0:19:21.74,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll do it the same way \Nwe used to conquer the Gin Drinkers Line. {lit: it's the same as ... breakthrough strategy/operation}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:22.41,0:19:24.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Alright, make arrangements for a massive landing. {lit: let's land all at once}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:33.46,0:19:37.71,Default,,0,0,0,,At 9 pm, the Japanese army \Nstarted the crossing towards the Hong Kong Island, {"landing" act. same as before}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:37.71,0:19:40.51,Default,,0,0,0,,virtually unnoticed by the British.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:41.47,0:19:44.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Not even when the Japanese soldiers \Nwere just some 90 meters away.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:46.24,0:19:48.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Second artillery observation post speaking.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:48.42,0:19:50.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Got nothing out of the ordinary going on.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:50.35,0:19:53.02,Default,,0,0,0,,- such was the report, made during the landing.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:04.49,0:20:07.33,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese army landing was a complete success.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:07.90,0:20:08.83,Default,,0,0,0,,However,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:08.83,0:20:13.27,Default,,0,0,0,,the British troops were also counterattacking fiercely, \Nhaving their escape route cut off.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:13.27,0:20:15.56,Default,,0,0,0,,The power plant, considered a vital position,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:15.56,0:20:21.26,Default,,0,0,0,,was defended by a hastily assembled volunteer formation{/self-organized unit}, comprised by about 70 British and French businessmen,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:21.26,0:20:22.41,Default,,0,0,0,,living in Hong Kong.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:22.88,0:20:29.68,Default,,0,0,0,,All had previous combat experience, but still, the youngest \Nmember of this unit was a 55 years old veteran. {lit: was a 55 y.o. old soldier}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:30.78,0:20:35.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Nevertheless, even after fully relieving \Nthe Indian Rajput battalion of fighting, {lit: after the rajput, whom they fought alongside with, withdrew}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:35.73,0:20:40.41,Default,,0,0,0,,this old men' company managed \Nto hold out on the power plant for a whole day.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:44.20,0:20:47.99,Default,,0,0,0,,It's nothing like how it was during World War I.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:47.99,0:20:52.54,Default,,0,0,0,,They gave me this medal \Nfor what I did in the Spanish Civil War. {I would assume he means the 1936-39 civil war as there weren't any wars in spain prior to that period; then again, said war only ended 2 years ago and he makes it sound as though it happened 20 ago so idk}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:52.54,0:20:53.39,Default,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:53.79,0:20:56.40,Default,,0,0,0,,The Indian Rajput Battalion is retreating in full!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:04.76,0:21:06.76,Default,,0,0,0,,And with tails between their legs! {lit: miserable; pitiable; shameful; deplorable; pathetic}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:07.24,0:21:10.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Let them{/does'nt matter}! We here will defend this place to death!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:32.41,0:21:36.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Keep it up! Chiang Kai-shek is already leading \Nhis large army to our succor!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:36.04,0:21:38.04,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese army will be smashed from behind!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:38.43,0:21:39.23,Default,,0,0,0,,However,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:39.66,0:21:44.38,Default,,0,0,0,,the promised allied army of Chiang Kai-shek, \Nwhom they put their reliance upon, never came.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:45.11,0:21:51.70,Default,,0,0,0,,It marched in the distance, far beyond the front line,{lit is "on the other side of the border/boundary" but idk what it may mean} \Nwest to east, just to disappeared again into the hinterland.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:51.70,0:21:54.48,Default,,0,0,0,,The British troops were plunged into desperation.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:55.02,0:21:59.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Governor-General, after a prolonged struggle, the reservoir \Neast of Mount Nicholson fallen to the Japanese.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:04.68,0:22:09.43,Default,,0,0,0,,In search of fresh water and provisions, \Nthe civilians are fleeing Hong Kong in rapid succession. {/one after another}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:19.73,0:22:22.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Prolonging the fight any further is impossible.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:28.34,0:22:33.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Prolonging the fighting any further \Nwould bring nothing a complete extermination of civilians.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:37.56,0:22:41.90,Default,,0,0,0,,December 25th, time is 5:20 pm. {actually the east of nicholson fell already on 20th so idk why they show this as related events}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:41.90,0:22:43.32,Default,,0,0,0,,The Governor-General of Hong Kong
Dialogue: 0,0:22:43.32,0:22:48.01,Default,,0,0,0,,and the overall commander of the British forces \NMajor General Maltby decided on a surrender.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:48.01,0:22:53.62,Default,,0,0,0,,At the Peninsula Hotel on the mainland part of Kowloon, \Nthey met with the Japanese army headquarters.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:53.62,0:22:56.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It was exactly on the day of Christmas.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:56.62,0:23:03.10,Default,,0,0,0,,And then, in the flickering candlelight, \Nas though in the celebration of the holy night,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:03.10,0:23:05.15,Default,,0,0,0,,the British signed a capitulation.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:05.50,0:23:10.30,Default,,0,0,0,,That was especially why the Governor-General of Hong Kong \Nwas not taking this defeat lightly. {lit: ...'s feeling of defeat was acute}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:10.30,0:23:11.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Stop it!
Dialogue: 0,0:23:11.24,0:23:13.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't do it no more!
Dialogue: 0,0:23:15.21,0:23:19.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Soon after, the Fall of Hong Kong, \Nwhich was believed to take four weeks at least,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:19.71,0:23:22.34,Default,,0,0,0,,was achieved in almost half the time.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:22.77,0:23:24.90,Default,,0,0,0,,A great victory achieved that promptly
Dialogue: 0,0:23:24.90,0:23:29.99,Default,,0,0,0,,consists of thousands of small details, that the commander, leading his unit forward, must at all times keep in his mind. {unsure what he means: commanding a division man always heart ought to do problem consists of}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:31.41,0:23:35.22,Default,,0,0,0,,This one time, the young offensive mindset \Nof a junior commanding officer {lit: judgement attack - I think he means "the decision to attack"}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:35.22,0:23:40.00,Default,,0,0,0,,availed him to cast off the shackles \Nof an overly cautious high command's strategy, {lit: born from the overly prudent plan/strategy, blew away the slack; looseness; play​ of the leading}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:40.00,0:23:41.92,Default,,0,0,0,,thus opening the way to victory.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:42.67,0:23:44.96,Default,,0,0,0,,When your subordinate exerts his vigor on you, {lit: when you come in contact with ...'s momentum}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:44.96,0:23:48.21,Default,,0,0,0,,can you adjust to the situation at hand \Nand fan that vigor further,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:48.21,0:23:51.51,Default,,0,0,0,,eventually spreading it across your entire organization?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:52.05,0:23:57.64,Default,,0,0,0,,The ability of a senior commander \Nto give such an overruling order is what victory hinges on{added victory}.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:58.51,0:24:08.28,Sign,,0,0,0,,The Pacific War taught us the preciousness of peace. \NBut also instilled numerous lessons on how to live.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:10.32,0:24:13.28,Default,,0,0,0,,In order to ensure a surprise landing \Non the Malay peninsula,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:13.28,0:24:17.62,Default,,0,0,0,,the Japanese set their sights on Britain's world-famous \Nunsinkable battleship Prince of Wales,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:17.62,0:24:19.75,Default,,0,0,0,,spotted patrolling off the coast of Malaya.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:20.50,0:24:22.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Aiming to live up to its fame{ of an unsinkable battleship},
Dialogue: 0,0:24:22.63,0:24:26.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Prince of Wales stands proudly, \Nprepared to repel an attack from any direction.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:26.54,0:24:32.13,Default,,0,0,0,,In response to this, it's engulfed in unrelenting \Nswarms from the sky by the Japanese Mitsubishi G4M's.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:31.82,0:24:38.86,Sign,,0,0,0,,Episode 7 \NHigh Seas Naval Battle for Malaya
Dialogue: 0,0:24:32.74,0:24:36.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Witness in the next "Decision": \NHigh Seas Naval Battle for Malaya.
Comment: 0,0:24:43.11,0:24:43.15,Default,,0,0,0,,{ch}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:44.35,0:24:48.86,Default,,0,0,0,,If you're a man, let's put your strength to test{男だったら　力を試せ}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:48.86,0:24:53.20,Default,,0,0,0,,If you are a man, keep your hopes sizzling{男だったら　希望(のぞみ)を燃やせ}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:53.20,0:24:57.56,Default,,0,0,0,,If you are a man, don't lose your heart{男だったら　くじけるな}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:57.56,0:25:06.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Because there's just you and me, a man and a man{俺もおまえも　男と男}
Dialogue: 0,0:25:06.13,0:25:14.51,Default,,0,0,0,,With crimson blood flowing in our veins all the same{おなじ真赤な　血が通う}
